Originally, {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} began as a form of nature worship, revering sacred objects like seas, mountains, and rivers as {{ill|shintai|ja|神体|1=Shintai|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (sacred objects). In early shrines, the enshrined deities often had no specific names or were unknown. In texts like the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and the {{ill|Manyoshu|ja|万葉集|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, only a few shrines, such as {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Sumiyoshi Shrine|ja|住吉神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, mention the names of their deities. Most shrines referred to their deities simply by appending "kami" to the shrine or place name. For example, the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|qq=draft|qq=draft}} lists mostly shrine names without specifying the names of the deities, suggesting that by the early 10th century, most deities did not have formal names.

From around the 10th century, deities began to be associated with specific functions or virtues, such as fire, water, or wood deities, beyond their original roles as tutelary gods of clans or regions. By the late {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the emergence of {{ill|Honji suijaku|ja|本地垂迹説|Honji suijaku=Honji suijaku|lt=Shinpon Butsujaku Setsu|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (theory of the Buddha as the true nature of kami) and its counterpart, {{ill|Han-Honji Suijaku Setsu|ja|反本地垂迹説|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Shinto superiority), spurred the personalization of deities. Names were often derived from Japanese mythology, local legends, or combinations of honorifics like "kami" (god), "mikoto" (honorific suffix), "hiko" (prince), or "hime" (princess). Additionally, influential deities such as {{ill|Inari|ja|稲荷|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Hachiman|ja|八幡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} were frequently {{ill|divided spirits|ja|分霊|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and enshrined as main deities.

This trend continued into the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, influenced by the {{ill|Fukko Shinto|ja|復古神道|Fukko Shinto=Fukko Shinto|lt=Restoration Shinto|qq=draft|qq=draft}} movement. By the {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (separation of Shinto and Buddhism) formalized this process, leading to widespread standardization of shrine practices and deity names, even at local and minor shrines.

However, the historical origins of many shrines remain uncertain. Even for {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|lt=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the identification of enshrined deities often relies on oral tradition, leading to "theories of succession" rather than definitive conclusions.

== Main and Auxiliary Deities ==
Shrines typically enshrine multiple deities. The primary deity is known as the '''main deity''' (主神, *shushin*), while others are referred to as '''auxiliary deities''' (配神, *haishin*) or '''secondary deities''' (相殿神, *aidono shin*).

The distinction between main and auxiliary deities began in the Meiji period with the establishment of {{ill|state-Ranked shrines|ja|官国幣社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. However, the concept of a "main deity and others" predates this and was expressed through terms like "front" (*mae*) and "secondary shrine" (*aidono*). Auxiliary deities typically have connections to the main deity but may also be included due to historical or political reasons. Some auxiliary deities later became the main deity of a shrine.

The term "aidono" (相殿, or 合殿) refers to a shrine enshrining multiple deities within a single {{ill|shaden|ja|社殿|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. When distinguishing between main and auxiliary deities, "aidono shin" refers specifically to auxiliary deities.

